In D, this is done with scope guard (or you can use destructors):<p><pre><code>    f = open("test.txt");
    scope(exit) f.close();
    print(f.read());
</code></pre>
The scope(exit) causes the following statement to be executed at the exit of the scope, regardless of how it leaves (return, goto, fall through, throw, etc.).<p>The advantage over try-finally is the 'finally' statement is associated with the open, rather than some arbitrary distance away.
